Let’s KNOWLet’s KNOWStarterMeans of RecreationUnit–III : Our Needs8
People work the whole day and get tired. They want to relax and have fun in 
different ways. Doing something to relax is called recreation. There are 
different types of recreational activities such as playing games, watching T.V., 
listening to music, going on a picnic, painting etc.
Such recreational activities relax and refresh us and make us happy and 
cheerful. They fill us with energy to go back to work again.
! Can you name the activities shown in the given pictures?
! Why do we do such activities?
We all love to play different kinds of games. Games provide us enjoyment on one 
hand and good health on the other. Sports and games play a major role in keeping a 
person fit and fine. They also help in boosting the immunity and increasing the 
intellectual and social skills of a person.

In schools, games are more technical and 
Indoor games– Games such as ludo, cards, chess, carrom, snakes and ladders, 
Chinese checkers etc. are usually played inside the home. So they are called indoor 
games.
Outdoor games– Games such as cricket, football, basket ball, volley ball, 
badminton, etc. are played in the field or play ground. So, they are called outdoor 
games.
Outdoor Games: 
An Integral Part of School CurriculumTraditional games– Some games are popular in villages and small towns rather 
than cities. Marbles, Kho-kho, hopscotch, spinning the top, gilli danda, flying kites 
etc. are some traditional games.
Environmental Studies-462

complex as they are played by following the rules and guidelines.
Rules in games– Every game has its own rules. It is very important that every sports 
person must play a fair game and obey all the rules of the game. Sometimes, to win, 
players out for unfair means which is an injustice to a game. To avoid fights and to 
play in a fair manner, a game can have a referee. However, the referee should be 
impartial and should be aware of the rules of the game.
Fair play– Games should be played fairly. We can ensure fair play by following 
certain points–
! We should have respect for the rules of the game and for the opponents.
! We should not intentionally hurt anyone or use bad words while playing.
! We should play the game with integrity.
! We must realize that it is not important to always win a game. We must play 
with the spirit of the game.
It was believed that girls cannot play as well as boys and there are some games 
which can only be played by boys. But this belief is completely vanished and we 
have many females like Sania Mirza, Saina Nehwal, P.T. Usha, Anjali Bhagwat, 
Apurvi Chandela, Anjum Chopra, Mithali Raj etc. who have established their names 
in the history of sports. Thus, they have broken the gender stereo type in games.
Breaking Gender StereotypeLike all children Raman loves to play. His parents encourage him to play different 
games. But he plays only during play time. He tells his friends, "We should divide

Raman plays with all the children of his colony. His friends are from all types of 
families in the neighbourhood. Some are poor, some are rich. His friends belong to 
different religions and casts. In the beginning, his friends didn't like to play with 
girls. But now, his friends have also realised that all games require skills and girls 
and boys can play together as equals.
On holidays, Raman goes out for a picnic with his family. He goes to fly kites with his 
father on some special days like Basant Panchami, Makar Sankranti, Independence 
Day etc. Sometimes, on festivals like Dussehra, Diwali, Teej etc he goes to a fair with 
his family to have fun but he never eats uncovered food from the vendors.
Raman also loves family functions like marriages and birthdays. He and his family 
enjoys many festivals like Diwali, Eid, Christmas and Gurupurab with all other 
people in the neighbourhood. Raman's family knows that we need recreational 
activities to keep ourselves fresh and fit.

People may have to travel from place to place for various reasons.
Ÿ They may buy goods from one place and sell them in another place.
Ÿ They may go in search of work.
Ÿ They may travel to enjoy their vacation.
Ÿ They may travel to attend some family functions etc. 
Travelling gives us the chance to engage in an activity to develop new skills and 
discover new culture of various places. Today, people use different means of 
Environmental Studies-468

transport to go from one place to another. Some of them are cars, buses, scooters, 
trains, aeroplanes etc.
Private and Public VehiclesVehicles like scooters, motorcycles and cars are used for our personal use. These 
are called private vehicles. We do not need to buy tickets for travelling in our 
private vehicles. We just need to get them filled with fuel.
But, when we travel by vehicles like buses, trains, ships and aeroplanes, we have to 
pay for travel. These are called public vehicles. When we use public transport, we 
need to buy tickets. We pay money to buy tickets. Now a days, we can book our 
tickets even through our mobile phones.
CurrencyEvery country has a particular type of money that is used for buying things in that 
country. It is called the currency of that country. Indian currency is called the rupee 
(!). It consists of coins and bank notes. 
Coins– Money made of metal is called a coin. Coins are round and flat and have two 
sides. On one side, its value and the year of minting is marked. This side is called 
head. On the other side is the National Emblem. This side is called tail.
Coins have a great historical importance. In ancient times, kings used coins made 
up of gold, silver or bronze known as mohars. Some coins of different values are 
shown below.
The smallest unit of Indian money is paise. One hundred paise make a rupee.
Bank notes ( Currency notes)– A currency note has two faces. On one face, each 
Indian note has its value written in the centre. All the notes are signed by the 
governor of the Reserve Bank of India (RBI) both in Hindi and English. Every note 
has a particular code number which is written at the top left hand corner and 
bottom right hand corner. A picture of our National Emblem is printed at the 
Environmental Studies-469

bottom right hand side and a picture of Mahatma Gandhi is slightly to the left of the 
centre. 
On the other face, each note has a picture of our National Monument. For 
example, 50 rupee note has a picture of Hampi, 10 rupee note has a picture of Sun 
temple and 500 rupee note has picture of Red fort. On the slight left hand side, you 
can see the value of the note written in words in different languages. 
Watermark– Watermark is an image or a pattern on a currency note. It can be seen 
only when light passes through it. Water mark is added to prevent circulation of 
fake currency.
Security thread– It is a thin ribbon woven into a note. This also prevents copying of 
currency notes.

Wrap- UpWrap- UpKey Points of the ChapterKnow Your National EmblemOur National Emblem has been taken from the Ashoka pillar of 
Sarnath. This emblem was adopted on 26 January, 1950, when 
India became a republic. It has a picture of four lions standing 
back to back. But we can see only three lions from one side. 
These four lions are mounted a ground abacus. The abacus 
shows an elephant, a galloping horse, a bull and a lion 
separated by a chakra over the bell shaped lotus. The words 
'Satyameva Jayate' meaning 'Truth Alone Triumphs' are 
inscribed below the abacus in Devnagari script.

means of transport.

CommunicationThe process of speaking, writing or using signs and sounds to share ideas and 
information is called communication. There are many ways of communicating with 
others. Most of the people communicate by speaking, listening and writing.
People who cannot speak and hear communicate through sign language i.e. 
through the movements of their hands and fingers.
Long ago, people used to send messages by pigeons and horse riders. Now-a-days 
we have various fast and easy means of communication.
The world's fastest train is the Shanghai Maglev.
